by javiereguiluz at 2016-01-13T10:19:19Z

I have a question about how to name and create Twig blocks which are easy to override.

If you have this code:

```html
<div class="global-actions">
    <div class="row">
        ...
    </div>
</div>
```

Which Twig blocks would you create for EasyAdmin?

**Option 1**

```twig
<div class="global-actions">
    <div class="row">
        {% block global_actions %}{% endblock %}
    </div>
</div>
```

**Option 2**

```twig
{% block global_actions %}
<div class="global-actions">
    <div class="row">
        ...
    </div>
</div>
{% endblock %}
```

**Option 3**

```twig
{% block global_actions %}
<div class="global-actions">
    <div class="row">
        {% block global_actions_inner %}{% endblock %}
    </div>
</div>
{% endblock %}
```

**Option 4**

```twig
{% block global_actions_wrapper %}
<div class="global-actions">
    <div class="row">
        {% block global_actions %}{% endblock %}
    </div>
</div>
{% endblock %}
```

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

by Pierstoval at 2016-01-13T11:00:34Z

@javiereguiluz I'd vote for option 4

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

by ogizanagi at 2016-01-13T12:27:13Z

Options 3 but:

```twig
{% block global_actions %}
<div class="global-actions">
    <div class="row">
        {% block global_actions_row %}{% endblock %}
    </div>
</div>
{% endblock %}
```

or if it make sense (but I doubt it will for most cases) :

```twig
{% block global_actions %}
<div class="global-actions">
    {% block global_actions_row %}
     <div class="row">
        {% block global_actions_row_inner %}{% endblock %}
     </div>
    {% endblock %}
</div>
{% endblock %}
```

Actually, it's hard to tell without more context. It really depends where it'll be.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

by Pierstoval at 2016-01-13T12:43:57Z

@ogizanagi Actually, having a `_wrapper` instead of `_inner` allows better understanding of the "easiness" of the override. Most of the time people will override what's inside the `div.row`, and the wrapper may certainly be here only to "hide" it all and leave the space blank. The row itself would be useful if there were needs in adding other rows to avoid having `</div><div class="row">` solitary in a template.

I don't know if I'm clear enough :stuck_out_tongue:

